On the the third anniversary of the mass abduction, Amnesty International has told Nigerian authorities more needs to be secure the release of the remaining captives. JOHANNESBURG On the third anniversary of the mass abduction in Chibok, Amnesty International is warning Nigerian authorities need to ramp up efforts to secure the release of the 195 young women still being held captive.The rights group says it stands firmly with bring back our girls campaigners and is calling on the state to account for the hostages.On this day in 2014, 276 schoolgirls were kidnapped from their dormitory by Boko Haram.Some were later found or rescued.Amnesty International says in the last 32 months there have been 41 other cases of mass abductions.